    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="letter">
                <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_702_1841-05_page01.jpg"/>
               
                <opener>
            
                        <date when="1841-05">April 1841</date>
                </opener>
                <p><note>51</note> 
                    My dearest <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">mother</persName> - Thank<lb/>
                    you for your own sweet words<lb/>
                    to me and I could fancy<lb/>
                    I heard them from your own<lb/>
                    voice and saw the kindness<lb/>
                    in your own eyes -<lb/>
                    I will not say that you cannot<lb/>
                    conceive for I really believe<lb/>
                    you can conceive &amp; believe <del>in</del><lb/>
                    the Delight we had in receiving<lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#CramP1">Cramptons</persName> letter - And I am<lb/>
                    sure you could not grudge<lb/>
                    me the greatest possible <choice> 
                    <orig>plea-<lb/>
                    sure</orig>
                    <reg>pleasure</reg>
                    </choice>
                    that money could <choice> 
                    <orig>pro-<lb/>
                    cure</orig>
                    <reg>procure</reg>
                    </choice>
                    for me - looking at the<lb/>
                    thing only in that light<lb/></p>
                    
                    <p>
                    It is <hi rend="underline">so</hi> satisfactory to have<lb/>
                    the best opinion - and a friends<lb/>
                    as well as a physicians interest<lb/>
                    in the case - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#CramP1">Crampton's</persName> assurance<lb/>
                    that he will continue in constant<lb/>
                    communication with <persName ref="./Personography.xml#NillX1">Nilligan</persName><lb/>
                    or <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DebrX1">Debron</persName> is such a satisfaction to<lb/>
                    us <hi rend="underline">here</hi> &amp; I am sure must be to<lb/>
                    all with you - And even to<lb/>
                    
                    <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_702_1841-05_page02.jpg"/>
                    you who are still suffering pain<lb/>
                    It must be such a comfort (as it<lb/>
                    is to us) to know that it will<lb/>
                    end - that the worst is over<lb/>
                    The crisis past - and the days<lb/>
                    of misery every day nearer &amp;<lb/>
                    nearer to an end - And that<lb/>
                    you will be as well as ever<lb/>
                    again - you patient mother!<lb/>
                    All so unused as you are to submit<lb/>
                    to illness and to being nursed<lb/>
                    you who always nursed me<lb/>
                    and every body but yourself!<lb/></p>
                
                    <p>
                    I really can hardly bring all that<lb/>
                    has happened to my mind<lb/>
                    - It has been so dreadfully<lb/>
                    strange - But all is coming<lb/>
                    round right now - We have<lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#CramP1">Cramptons</persName> assurance - insurance<lb/>
                    for it - I so like his giving that<lb/>
                    insurance <del>careless of</del> <add>willing to hang all</add> his own <choice> 
                    <orig>reputa-<lb/>
                    tion</orig>
                    <reg>reputation</reg>
                    </choice>
                    as a medical prophet <del>in order</del><lb/>
                    to save us from any unnecessary<lb/>
                    agony of suspense &amp; anxiety<lb/></p>
                
                    <p>
                    I hope you will like his letter<lb/>
                    as we do.<lb/>
                    and <unclear>again</unclear> I thank you dearest<lb/>
                    
                    <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_702_1841-05_page03.jpg"/>
                    <note>52</note>
                    mother for your kind acceptance<lb/>
                    of my heartfelt grateful affection.<lb/></p>
                
                    <p>
                    - As soon as ever <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName><lb/>
                    is well enough to be left alone<lb/>
                    I shall come to you - But not<lb/>
                    before - So let your mind be<lb/>
                    quite easy on that subject<lb/></p>
                
                    <p>
                    Mine is quite easy about you<lb/>
                    - I know that you have the best<lb/>
                    &amp; kindest of nurses &amp; that you<lb/>
                    have now the best of medical<lb/>
                    advice and that all that was<lb/>
                    done was done rightly And<lb/>
                    that I can be of no use or pleasure<lb/>
                    to you just at present - not till<lb/>
                    you are convalescent &amp; able<lb/>
                    to hear nonsense &amp;c &amp;c -<lb/></p>
                
                    <p>
                    By that time as sure as I am<lb/>
                    alive I shall be beside you<lb/>
                    and happy I shall be to feel<lb/>
                    your hand in mine again<lb/>
                    &amp; see you sitting up quite <unclear>sprank</unclear><lb/>
                    - as thin &amp; as pale as you please<lb/>
                    - for that I shall be quite prepared<lb/></p>
                
                    <p>
                    For all about <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName> - See or Hear<lb/>
                    Bulletin - She has nothing more to say<lb/>
                    to you but her Love &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WilsL1">Lestocks</persName> with ME's<lb/>
                </p>
               
            </div>
